<paragraph id="8B9D1232BB49FFC625AECD77FF7BE277" blockId="2.[151,1436,580,838]" pageId="2" pageNumber="43">
<bibRefCitation id="EFB36FC3BB49FFC625AECD77FECBE36F" author="Barroso, G. M." box="[151,329,580,606]" pageId="2" pageNumber="43" pagination="1 - 281" refId="ref6519" refString="Barroso, G. M. (1976) Subtribo Baccharidinae Hoffman. Estudo das especies ocorrentes no Brasil. Rodriguesia 28: 1 - 281." type="journal article" year="1976">Barroso (1976)</bibRefCitation>
only indicated 
<emphasis id="B956CE20BB49FFC624C6CD77FD1CE36C" box="[511,670,580,605]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="43">Sellow d2013</emphasis>
as “ 
<typeStatus id="5499AC90BB49FFC627F6CD77FCB9E36F" box="[719,827,580,606]" pageId="2" pageNumber="43">holotype</typeStatus>
” of 
<taxonomicName id="4C2269B1BB49FFC62654CD77FBB5E36C" authorityName="de Candolle" authorityYear="1836" box="[877,1079,580,605]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Baccharis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="2" pageNumber="43" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="helichrysoides">
<emphasis id="B956CE20BB49FFC62654CD77FBB5E36C" box="[877,1079,580,605]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="43">B. helichrysoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, without citing any herbarium acronym. Although effectively a lectotypification, her choice was superseded owing to a previous lectotypification by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFB36FC3BB49FFC624B2CDA2FDF4E39A" author="Malagarriga Heras, R. P. &amp; Irmao Teodoro Luis" box="[395,630,657,683]" pageId="2" pageNumber="43" pagination="1 - 61" refId="ref7201" refString="Malagarriga Heras, R. P. [as Irmao Teodoro Luis] (1957) Para o estudo da Flora Sul-Riograndense qual o valor da &quot; Flora Brasiliensis &quot; de Martius? Contribuicoes do Instituto Geobiologico La Salle 8: 1 - 61." type="journal article" year="1957">Malagarriga (1957)</bibRefCitation>
based on the same material in P. The 
<typeStatus id="5499AC90BB49FFC6217CCDA2FB2FE39A" box="[1093,1197,657,683]" pageId="2" pageNumber="43">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName id="4C2269B1BB49FFC621E1CDA2FAFDE39B" authorityName="Gardner" authorityYear="1848" box="[1240,1407,657,682]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Baccharis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="2" pageNumber="43" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="lanuginosa">
<emphasis id="B956CE20BB49FFC621E1CDA2FAFDE39B" box="[1240,1407,657,682]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="43">B. lanuginosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is stated as being from 
<date id="FF9C34F2BB49FFC624A0CD8BFDDDE3E3" box="[409,607,696,722]" pageId="2" pageNumber="43" value="1840-09">September 1840</date>
on the type specimen sheet. However, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFB36FC3BB49FFC6217ACD8BFA82E3E3" author="Gardner, G." box="[1091,1280,696,722]" pageId="2" pageNumber="43" pagination="78 - 90" refId="ref6716" refString="Gardner, G. (1848) Contributions towards a Flora of Brazil, being the distinctive characters of some new species of Compositae, belonging to the tribe Asteroideae. The London journal of botany: containing figures and descriptions of such plants as recommend themselves by their novelty, rarity, history, or uses: together with botanical notices and information and occasional portraits and memoirs of eminent botanists 7: 78 - 90." type="journal article" year="1848">Gardner (1848)</bibRefCitation>
wrote ‘ 
<date id="FF9C34F2BB49FFC62065CD8BFF55E3C8" pageId="2" pageNumber="43" value="1840-08">Aug. 1840</date>
’ in the protologue and cited the collection as ‘4900,1’. In the ‘Catalogue’ of his collections, the entry of 
<taxonomicName id="4C2269B1BB49FFC625AECC35FEBFE22E" authorityName="Gardner" authorityYear="1848" box="[151,317,774,799]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Baccharis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="2" pageNumber="43" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="lanuginosa">
<emphasis id="B956CE20BB49FFC625AECC35FEBFE22E" box="[151,317,774,799]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="43">B. lanuginosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was clearly added relatively late when Gardner realized he had a ‘new species’ (Hind, pers. comm.).
</paragraph>
